lish: variant of   Foulks  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Foulks","meanings":["English: from Middle English, Anglo-Norman French <i>Folkes</i>, <i>Foukes</i>, an Old French nominative form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Fulco</i>, which is derived from a linguistic element meaning ‘folk, people’. See also   Foulk   and   Volk  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Fowkes was born in 1530, in Brewood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Roger Fowke, was 37 and his mother, Margaret Wharwood, was 50. He married Joan Leveson in 1555, in Brewood, Staffordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He lived in Tranmere, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom in 1881. He died on 18 February 1558, in Brewood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 28, and was buried in Brewood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1530–18 February 1558":"1530–18. veebruar 1558","1530–1558":"1530–1558","1530–1572":"1530–1572","1555–Female":"1555–Surnud","1556–Female":"1556–Surnud","1558–1594":"1558–1594","1494–1544":"1494–1544","1480–1561":"1480–1561","1561":"1561","1594":"1594","1572":"1572","1494":"1494","1480":"1480","18 February 1558":"18. veebruar 1558","1558":"1